The E-news Express compared its existing landing page to landing page with new features. The online news portal limited its data collection to 100 landing page visitors: 50 current landing page visitors (the control) and 50 new feature landing page visitors (the treatment). The data collected includes an assigned user ID, control vs treatment, time spent on page, conversion, and the visitors preferred language.

Do landing page visitors spend more time on the new landing page (treatment) than the old landing page (control)?¶
Let 1, 2 be the time spend on the old landing page and the time spent on the new landing page respectively.


We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: 1=2


against the alternate hypothesis


$H_a$: 12











In [106]:

Assessing whether the T-test assumptions are satisfied or not¶
Continuous data - Yes, the time spent on the page is measured on a continuous scale.


Normally distributed populations - Yes, the visuals above appear to be normal distributions.


Independent populations - Although the data originally was from one population, we divided it separately to isolate each group. 
We originally assume the beginning population so this process results in two random, independent populations.


Unequal population standard deviations - As the sample standard deviations are different, the population standard deviations may be assumed to be different.


Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample a simple random sample.


All assumptions are met. We can use two sample T-test for this problem.











In [108]:



     


#import the required functions
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(abtest1['time_spent_on_the_page'], abtest2['time_spent_on_the_page'].dropna(), equal_var = True, alternative = 'two-sided')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)



     


















    
    






The p-value is  0.000263224705619001




















As the p-value is less than .05, we must fail to reject the null hypothesis. A new landing page does not statistically increase the time visitors spend on the E-news express portal.











Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶
Two proportion z-test¶
Let p1,p2 be the proportions of conversions of the control and treatment landing pages respectively.


The E-news Express will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: p1=p2


against the alternate hypothesis


$H_a$: p1<p2











Let's test whether the Z-test assumptions are satisfied or not¶
Binomally distributed population - Yes, a visitor is either converted or not.


Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.


Can the binomial distribution approximated to normal distribution - Yes. For binary data, CLT works slower than usual. The standard thing is to check whether np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10. Here, n and p refer to the sample size and sample proportion respectively.











In [128]:



     


# import the required fuction
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# set the counts of defective items
conversions = np.array([21, 33])

# set the sample sizes
landing_page_visitors = np.array([50, 50])

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(conversions, landing_page_visitors)
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))



     


















    
    






The p-value is 0.016052616408112556




















As the p-value is less than .05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. The conversion rate for the new page is not statistically better than the old page.











A landing page with new features will increase the conversion rate.¶
We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: Subscriber conversion is independent of the landing page.


against the alternate hypothesis


$H_a$: A landing page with new features will increase visitor conversion.

Time spent on the page affects the conversion rate¶
We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: Subscriber conversion is independent of the time spent on the landing page.


against the alternate hypothesis


$H_a$: More time spent on the landing page will increase visitor conversion.

The preferred language affects the conversion rate¶

against the alternate hypothesis

Is the mean time spent on each landing page different for each preferred language?¶
Let 1,2,3 be the means of preferred languages of visitors speaking Spanish, French, and English respectively.


We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: 1=2=3


against the alternative hypothesis


$H_a$: At least one preferred language is different from the rest.

Now, the normality and equality of variance assumptions need to be checked.¶
For testing of normality, Shapiro-Wilks test is applied to the response variable.


For equality of variance, Levene test is applied to the response variable.


Shapiro-Wilk’s test¶
We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: Preferred Language follows a normal distribution against


against the alternative hypothesis


$H_a$: Preferred language does not follow a normal distribution











In [121]:



     


# Assumption 1: Normality
# import the required function
from scipy import stats

# find the p-value
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(abtest['time_spent_on_the_page']) 
print('The p-value is', p_value)



     


















    
    






The p-value is 0.5643684267997742




















Since p-value of the test is very large, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the response follows the normal distribution.











Levene’s test¶
We will test the null hypothesis


$H_0$: All the population variances are equal


against the alternative hypothesis


$H_a$: At least one variance is different from the rest











In [122]:



     


#Assumption 2: Homogeneity of Variance
#import the required function
from scipy.stats import levene
statistic, p_value = levene( abtest['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest['language_preferred']=="Spanish"], 
                                   abtest['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest['language_preferred']=="French"], 
                                   abtest['time_spent_on_the_page'][abtest['language_preferred']=="English"])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)



     


















    
    






The p-value is 0.06515086840327314




















Since the p-value is larger than .05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homogeneity of variances.











Are the assumptions are satisfied?¶
The populations are normally distributed - Yes, the normality assumption is verified using the Shapiro-Wilks test.


Samples are independent simple random samples - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.


Population variances are equal - Yes, the homogeneity of variance assumption is verified using the Levene's test.











In [124]:



     


#import the required function
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# perform one-way anova test
test_stat, p_value = f_oneway(abtest.loc[abtest['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              abtest.loc[abtest['language_preferred'] == 'French', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              abtest.loc[abtest['language_preferred'] == 'English', 'time_spent_on_the_page'])
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))



     


















    
    






The p-value is 0.8665610536012648




















Since p-value is greater than .05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence we do not have statistical evidence that preferred language affects conversion rates.











Multiple Comparison test (Tukey HSD)¶
In order to identify for which preferred language mean of time spent on the new page is different from other groups, the null hypothesis is


$H_0$: 1=2 and 1=3 and 2=3


against the alternative hypothesis


$H_a$: 12 or 13 or 23











In [126]:



     


#import the required function
from statsmodels.stats.multicomp import pairwise_tukeyhsd

# perform multiple pairwise comparison (Tukey HSD)
m_comp = pairwise_tukeyhsd(endog = abtest['time_spent_on_the_page'], groups = abtest['language_preferred'], alpha = 0.05)
print(m_comp)
